                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17690222-22-victim252 t17690222-22-viclabel131"></join> at Paris. On the 18th of January I went into a public house to get a pint of purl; I left the hat, which I used to wear (it is property Mr. Panshard's ) on the coach: I was gone about ten minutes; when I came back, my hat was gone. A chairman told me, he saw a man, describing the prisoner, come out of the stable; I overtook him in Greek-street, over-against the end of Queen-street: he had the hat in his pocket and a handkerchief over it. (Produced in court and deposed to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I had the hat to be sure, but I took it in a joke. I was walking quietly along the street<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="176902220016"></xptr> with it to a public house; if I had taken it with an intent to steal it, I could have made off and he never seen me any more.</p>
